Description: The General Theological Seminary is a school.
Headquarters Regions: Greater New York Area, East Coast, Northeastern US
Full Description: General Theological Seminary (GTS) in New York City is a community-oriented Episcopal seminary. Academics include theological and ministerial degrees, as well as programs for those who wish to work as spiritual counselors. GTS offers graduate-level master’s and doctoral degrees in:   * Divinity   * Sacred Theology   * Theology GTS also operates the Center for Spiritual Direction. Here, one may earn a certificate or master’s degree in Spiritual Direction or Spiritual Guidance for Children. Through these programs, students learn how to help others define their identity in the context of Christian spirituality. Many master’s degree students simultaneously earn this certification in order to enhance their ministerial practice. GTS’ sense of community is probably its most distinctive feature. GTS fosters closeness between students and faculty through various college life activities, which include morning and evening prayer services and community meals. GTS hosts academic and spiritual lectures and participates in international theological seminars, as well. Since GTS is located in the heart of New York City, students also have access to numerous spiritual, religious, cultural and recreational activities. Degree applicants must have a bachelor’s degree. Materials required for admissions include transcripts, an admissions application, an autobiographical essay and four letters of recommendation. Applicants will also need to interview with the seminary’s faculty or staff. GTS offers federal financial aid packages, which consist of loans, grants, work-study or a combination of these. GTS also offers several scholarships, including the Bishop Hamilton H. Kellogg Scholarship, which covers the majority of tuition costs. All of these awards are given to students who qualify.

Description: Hypertension Diagnostics designs and manufactures non-invasive medical devices that detect subtle changes in the elasticity of arteries.
Headquarters Regions: Greater Minneapolis-Saint Paul Area, Great Lakes, Midwestern US
Full Description: Hypertension Diagnostics, Inc. designs, develops, manufactures, and markets proprietary noninvasive medical devices that detect subtle changes in the elasticity of arteries in the United States and internationally. Its patented CVProfilor allows a physician to non-invasively assess the elasticity of small and large arteries, of which small artery elasticity is the earliest and sensitive marker of cardiovascular disease. The company offers CVProfilor DO-2020, which provides a patient’s arterial elasticity indices used in the assessment for underlying vascular disease; CVProfilor MD-3000 that offers a sensitive and specific guide to the presence of blood vessel disease; and HD/PulseWave CR-2000 research cardiovascular profiling system for research purposes. Its products collect 30 seconds of blood pressure waveform data, perform an analysis of the digitized blood pressure waveforms, and generate a CVProfile report that contains information on blood pressure, heart rate, pulse pressure, body surface area, body mass index, and both C1-large and C2-small artery elasticity indices. The company sells its products to primary care physicians, cardiologists, health care professionals, trained medical personnel, research investigators at academic medical research centers, government institutes, cardiovascular specialists, and pharmaceutical firms. It markets its products through a representative organization in the United States. Hypertension Diagnostics, Inc. was founded in 1988 and is headquartered in Eagan, Minnesota.
Industry Groups: Biotechnology, Health Care, Manufacturing, Science and Engineering
